{"type":"message","id":"04a6b373","parentId":"f52f635c","timestamp":"2026-04-06T10:36:01.475Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"`agents.defaults.timeoutSeconds` is 1200 (20 minutes). But the cron job has its own `payload.timeoutSeconds` of 600. \n\nThe issue is that the isolated session itself might have a different timeout. Let me look at the cron job's full payload to see if there's an isolated session timeout.Actually, let me look at the problem differently. The skill is sending sections ONE AT A TIME. This means:\n1. The model processes section 1 and sends a Telegram message\n2. The model then waits for the NEXT agent turn to process section 2\n3. But in an isolated session, each agent turn is a separate API call\n\nSo the flow might be:\n- Agent turn 1: Process header + send → generates response ( Telegram message sent)\n\n\n- Agent turn 2: Process weather → generate response (Telegram message sent)\n- Agent turn 3: Process Bible verse → generate response\n- ... and so on\n\nEach agent turn involves the model generating a response. The total time is the sum of all these turns plus any pauses between them. If the session is isolated and each turn is separate, the timeout for EACH TURN might be what's killing us.\n\nBut the skill instructions say to send sections one at a time... which implies the model should do ALL the work in ONE turn and send messages incrementally, not in separate turns.\n\nLooking at the SKILL.md more carefully, the pattern is clear: each section gets its own message sent immediately, then the model moves to the next section. This happens within a single conversation turn, not across multiple agent turns. The model generates the content for section 1, I send it via Telegram, then the model continues with section 2 in the same turn. So theoretically this should work in one turn.\n\nBut the timeout suggests it's NOT working that way—either the model is treating each section as a separate turn, or something about the message sending is triggering a new turn. The real issue might be that after sending message 1, when the model tries to send message 2, the isolated session has some kind of turn limit or the message tool itself is causing a new turn to start, which then hits a timeout. I'm wondering if the real problem is that each Telegram message counts as a new agent turn in the isolated session, which has its own timeout of around 60-110 seconds. So the first turn handles sections 1-3, then it times out before getting to the rest. I should increase the cron timeout and fix the Gmail integration to use gog instead.","thinkingSignature":"1a8d4a037c422554155aa5095b25333741d429fbbeb52de4c4c2147da2d7098c"},{"type":"text","text":"OK found the real issues. Let me fix both:\n\n1. **Gmail auth is broken** → Update skill to use `gog` (already authenticated ✅)\n2. **Cron timeout too short** → Bump from 600s → 1800s\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_5ja8zbhwn7qa_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"edits":[{"oldText":"### 4. Email Summary\n\n**Source:** Gmail API (NOT gog CLI - gog is limited to ~12 emails)\n\n**Account:** rtg.bobby@gmail.com\n\n**CRITICAL:** Use Python with Gmail API directly. gog CLI only shows ~12 emails and will miss most of your inbox!\n\n**Python Script:**\n```python\nimport json\nfrom google.oauth2.credentials import Credentials\nfrom google.auth.transport.requests import Request\nfrom googleapiclient.discovery import build\nfrom datetime import datetime, timedelta\n\nwith open('/Users/bobbygalletta/.config/gmail_oauth/credentials.json') as f:\n    data = json.load(f)\n    \ncreds = Credentials(\n    token=data['token'],\n    refresh_token=data['refresh_token'],\n    client_id=data['client_id'],\n    client_secret=data['client_secret'],\n    token_uri=data['token_uri'],\n)\n\nif creds.expired:\n    creds.refresh(Request())\n\nservice = build('gmail', 'v1', credentials=creds)\n\n# Get emails from yesterday AND today\nyesterday = (datetime.now() - timedelta(days=1)).strftime(\"%Y/%m/%d\")\nquery = f'in:inbox after:{yesterday}'\n\nres = service.users().messages().list(userId='me', q=query, maxResults=100).execute()\nmsgs = res.get('messages', [])\nprint(f'Total: {len(msgs)}')\n\nfor m in msgs:\n    msg = service.users().messages().get(userId='me', id=m['id'], format='full').execute()\n    headers = {h['name']: h['value'] for h in msg['payload'].get('headers', [])}\n    sender = headers.get('From', '')\n    subject = headers.get('Subject', '')\n    date_h = headers.get('Date', '')\n    labels = msg.get('labelIds', [])\n    is_unread = 'UNREAD' in labels\n    print(f'[{\"UNREAD\" if is_unread else \"READ\"}] {sender[:30]} | {subject[:60]}')","newText":"### 4. Email Summary\n\n**Source:** gog CLI (authenticated and working)\n\n**Account:** rtg.bobby@gmail.com\n\n**Command:**\n```bash\ngog gmail search 'newer_than:1d in:inbox' --max 100 --account rtg.bobby@gmail.com\n```\n\n**CRITICAL:** The old Python/Gmail API script is BROKEN (auth expired). Always use gog instead!"}],"file":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/skills/morning-brief/SKILL.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":35583,"output":1225,"cacheRead":26978,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":63786,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775471736385,"responseId":"0622bf788628c0622fbfc5f51b7e80b0"}}
