{"type":"message","id":"7686b893","parentId":"97ce165e","timestamp":"2026-04-07T00:04:03.389Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Looking at the cron runs, I can see:\n1. The 5:30 AM run today (runAtMs: 1775471768938) actually **succeeded** — \"status: ok\", delivered: true\n2. Before that there was one that timed out (109 seconds in)\n\nBut wait, let me look more carefully. The first entry shows:\n- status: ok\n- runAtMs: 1775471768938\n\nThat's the one that succeeded — it ran after I fixed the Gmail issue. But the timestamp... let me check. 1775471768938 ms from epoch.\n\nActually, looking at the timestamps:\n\n\n- runAtMs 1775471768938 = April 6, 2026, roughly 11:29 AM EDT (after the morning brief)\n- The one before it with error: 1775471369026 = a few seconds earlier\n\nSo there were two runs close together — the first one failed with a timeout, but then it automatically retried and succeeded.\n\nWait, actually the manual run I triggered earlier was at around 11:16 AM (1775471369026) and it timed out. But the 5:30 AM scheduled run should have been at around 9:30 AM UTC. Let me check if those timestamps align with the actual cron schedule.\n\nThe 5:30 AM EDT scheduled run (which is 09:30 UTC) should have run at 1775467800000, but that's not showing in the truncated output. Looking at the first entry, it has runAtMs: 1775471768938, which is 11:29 AM EDT — that's way later than the 5:30 AM slot. So either I'm misreading which run this is, or there's a significant delay between when the cron was supposed to trigger and when it actually executed. I'm noticing the cron runs API is returning entries in reverse chronological order, so I need to look at the full picture rather than assuming the first result is the most recent one. The timestamp conversion shows the successful 5:30 AM run completed around 11:29 AM EDT with a 130-second duration, but there's also a failed run at 11:16 AM that timed out after 109 seconds — and I should verify which entry corresponds to which run and whether there's another scheduled run I'm missing. The 5:30 AM run did complete successfully after a 130-second execution time, not the 109-second timeout that failed, so the system is functioning properly now. The timeout errors he's seeing might be from a different cron job or a delayed notification from an earlier failure. Looking at the run history, the 5:30 AM cron actually succeeded on its second attempt—109 seconds wasn't enough, but the retry with the 1800-second timeout completed in 130 seconds. I should check if there are other cron jobs still failing and sending him error notifications.","thinkingSignature":"cd59026cd94776c52b80777b487b1e0bbffc5002fbb9ea9a12deca84b3a9b3d6"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_7r8pi88hdw0c_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"openclaw cron list 2>/dev/null | grep -v \"laundry\" | grep \"error\\|ok\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":71197,"output":643,"cacheRead":21957,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":93797,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775520218069,"responseId":"06237cda06b4d48a0a6a3f719de30dbf"}}
