{"type":"message","id":"4b2f94e2","parentId":"a93623f6","timestamp":"2026-04-07T00:18:38.712Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"All set to 1200s timeout and MiniMax-M2.7 model. They should be fine. But they're timing out at 74-86 seconds. The issue is that the cron job's isolated session is timing out before a response is generated.\n\nThis is very strange - 1200s timeout but timing out at 74-86s. This suggests the cron job is using a different timeout, or the isolated session type has a different limit.\n\nWait - looking at the error message: \"Request timed out before a response was generated. Please try again, or increase `agents.defaults.timeoutSeconds` in your config.\"\n\nBut agents.defaults.timeoutSeconds is already 1200. \n\nSo either the cron job payload timeout is being ignored, or there's something else controlling the actual timeout for isolated sessions. Let me look at the cron job's actual payload configuration - these all have model and timeout set to 1200, but maybe there's a separate setting for how long the isolated session waits for that first response.\n\nLooking at the timing more carefully: the run started at ts=1775520000079 and errored at ts=1775520074277, which is only about 74 seconds. But the timeout is set to 1200 seconds. This gap suggests the issue isn't the timeout itself - something else is causing the cron job to fail before it even gets a response.\n\nI think what's happening is the cron job triggers the isolated session, the session starts and begins processing, but then it hits an internal timeout or gets blocked somehow. The \"Request timed out before a response was generated\" message indicates the isolated session completed its work but the main session never received the completion signal back. Let me check the actual session transcript to see what the isolated session was doing during those 74 seconds.","thinkingSignature":"35126044ef94a0cba8653f35527b57a35be616a6c9514ac05ea19c87cd9c9b71