{"type":"message","id":"f99db32a","parentId":"d5776399","timestamp":"2026-04-07T00:19:39.710Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The session is `agent:main:cron:7ea307af-cd86-49f7-9975-723670e3b304:run:784cf9c1-3bd6-468f-8cfd-b832ba0f0425`. These cron jobs use isolated sessions and the session completes with an error. The isolated session itself is what times out.\n\nThe issue seems to be that the isolated session (which runs the cron job task) is timing out. The \"Request timed out before a response was generated\" message means the agent in the isolated session didn't produce a response within the timeout.\n\nThis could be happening because:\n1. The task the cron is running is hitting a long operation (like reading many files, running complex scripts)\n\n\n2. The isolated session itself has a different timeout than what's configured\n\nI can't directly view isolated session transcripts since they're separate from the main session history, but I should check the tasks list to see what's actually running in these cron jobs. Looking at the cron job configuration, it specifies `MiniMax-M2.7` as the model and `1200` seconds as the timeout, yet the actual runs are timing out at 74 seconds instead.\n\nThe \"Request timed out before a response was generated\" error suggests the model call itself is taking longer than expected, or there's an issue with how the isolated session is handling the task. The isolated session might have its own built-in timeout separate from what I've configured in the cron job settings.\n\nLooking at the openclaw config schema, I can see `agents.defaults.subagents.runTimeoutSeconds` is set to 1200 and `maxConcurrent` is set to 4, which might be controlling isolated session behavior. The most practical fix would be to either simplify what these cron jobs are actually doing, or just delete the ones that aren't critical—like the ones that are timing out repeatedly. The actual problem is that the Battery Monitor is stuck on `local-tiny` instead of `MiniMax-M2.7`, so fixing that model should resolve the immediate issue. For the others timing out, the real solution is likely streamlining their scripts rather than just adjusting timeouts, though I should check what those cron jobs are actually configured to do first.","thinkingSignature":"fce53af87a52637a97d6609148d49b8d04de099639cd0a6ab423f1590c7c5cf1"},{"type":"text","text":"These crons are timing out at ~74s despite having 1200s configured. The issue is the isolated session itself. Let me check what these tasks are actually doing:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_qlkgi3szvruc_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"openclaw cron list --json 2>/dev/null | python3 -c \"\nimport json, sys\ndata = json.load(sys.stdin)\nfor job in data.get('jobs', []):\n    if job.get('id') in ['7ea307af-cd86-49f7-9975-723670e3b304', '4ad06060-6fbc-4762-80e4-9dcdb6ac7a0d', '487e71b7-8898-4da8-8e53-5237c045750c', '9865c737-e428-4480-bd2e-3420944dc2b5', '7b25e1f1-42f6-4fde-8d49-fa3c608899d7']:\n        print(f\\\"=== {job['name']} ===\\\")\n        print(f\\\"Message: {job.get('message','')[:200]}\\\")\n        print()\n\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":76519,"output":727,"cacheRead":21957,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":99203,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775521163020,"responseId":"0623808ba13346a4bd95a3accaeeb6f2"}}
